ydpng.js\\\",\\\"/_next/static/chunks/0d3shmwh5_nmn.js\\\",\\\"/_next/static/chunks/0lnjlo~xn6fto.js\\\"],\\\"Reveal\\\"]\\n1d:T3397,\"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,\"\\u003ch1\\u003eWild Turkey Hunting in Michigan's Thumb — Guided Hunts with Hotshot Outfitters\\u003c/h1\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eMichigan's turkey population is one of the great wildlife management success stories in the state. Turkeys were extirpated from Michigan by the early 20th century and have been reestablished through careful management to the point where they now occupy habitat from the Upper Peninsula to the southernmost counties. Huron County is no exception — the agricultural patchwork and woodlot cover of Michigan's Thumb supports a healthy turkey population, and the birds here are big, vocal, and huntable in a landscape that rewards the kind of intimate knowledge our guides have built over 20+ years.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eHotshot Outfitters guides wild turkey hunts in Michigan's Thumb, both spring and fall. If you're looking for guided turkey hunting in Michigan, this page will tell you exactly what to expect.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eWhy Michigan's Thumb Produces Turkeys\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eEastern wild turkeys thrive in the kind of habitat that defines Huron County: a mix of hardwood timber, open agricultural fields for feeding, and brushy edge cover that provides thermal and predator protection. The agricultural diversity of the Thumb — corn, soybeans, wheat, and hay fields interspersed with oak woodlots and cedar stands — gives turkeys exactly what they need year-round.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eSpring toms in Michigan's Thumb gobble hard. The terrain provides natural staging areas — field edges where gobblers strut, woodlot openings where they drum and display — that are predictable once you've spent seasons watching turkey behavior on specific properties. Our guides have done that work. They know which ridgelines hold roosting birds, which agricultural fields become strut zones in April, and which creek bottoms connect the pieces.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eMichigan Wild Turkey Season Dates\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eMichigan's turkey hunting framework includes both spring and fall seasons, with the spring season being the more popular and widely practiced. The MI DNR manages turkey hunting through a draw/license system — some zones require applying for a license through the Limited License Application (LLA) process, while others may have over-the-counter availability depending on turkey population management goals for a given zone.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eSpring Turkey Season\\u003c/strong\\u003e: Typically opens in mid-to-late April and runs through late May. The season is divided into multiple periods (Early, Middle, Late), each available to hunters who draw the corresponding license. Check current MI DNR regulations for exact dates and period structures each year.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eFall Turkey Season\\u003c/strong\\u003e: A fall season is available in many Michigan Wildlife Management Units (WMUs) and typically runs from mid-October through mid-November. Fall hunting allows either-sex harvest in most units, while spring season is limited to bearded birds (gobblers and bearded hens).\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eLicense System\\u003c/strong\\u003e: Michigan turkey licenses for many units are allocated through the LLA draw system. Applications are typically submitted in the winter prior to spring season. Non-residents can also apply for turkey licenses. Check the MI DNR turkey page for current WMU availability, license types, and application deadlines. Drawing a tag is the first step — contact us about booking once you have your license.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eAlways verify current season dates, license requirements, and WMU-specific rules at the \\u003ca href=\\\"https://www.michigan.gov/dnr\\\"\\u003eMI DNR website\\u003c/a\\u003e.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eWhat to Expect on a Guided Turkey Hunt\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eSpring turkey hunting is one of the most interactive and engaging hunting experiences available in Michigan. You're not waiting passively — you're having a conversation with a gobbler, reading his behavior, and adapting in real time. When a big tom commits and comes in drumming, every step he takes toward you cranks the tension higher. It's addictive.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003ePre-Hunt Scouting\\u003c/strong\\u003e: Your guide will locate roosted birds on the properties we access before your hunt. Knowing where birds roost sets up the whole morning — you position between the roost and the likely strut zone, and the birds walk to you rather than you chasing them.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eSetup\\u003c/strong\\u003e: Most spring turkey hunting is done from a ground blind or natural vegetation ambush point. We'll be set up before first light, decoys out, ready when the birds pitch down from roost. The position and decoy configuration are matched to the terrain and the specific birds we're hunting.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eCalling\\u003c/strong\\u003e: Spring gobbler calling — yelps, clucks, purrs, and cackles — is the primary tool for closing the distance on a fired-up tom. Your guide will manage the calling, reading the gobbler's responses and adjusting the cadence accordingly. If a bird hangs up 100 yards away and won't commit, there's a reason, and an experienced caller reads that and changes the approach.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eFall Hunting\\u003c/strong\\u003e: Fall turkey hunting in Michigan is a different experience. The technique shifts to locating flocks, scattering them, then calling the reassembled birds back to your position. It's less predictable than spring but deeply satisfying when it works.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eMichigan's Thumb Turkey Habitat\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eThe properties we access in Huron County provide the habitat diversity that makes turkey hunting productive and interesting:\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eOak and Mixed Hardwood Woodlots\\u003c/strong\\u003e: Mast-producing oaks are key turkey habitat in fall, providing acorns that concentrate birds in predictable areas. Spring toms use hardwood timber for roosting and as display staging areas.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eAgricultural Field Edges\\u003c/strong\\u003e: The transition between crop fields and timber is a classic turkey strut zone in spring. Gobblers use open field edges where they can see and be seen, and they'll work these edges for hours on a good spring morning.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eCreek and Drainage Corridors\\u003c/strong\\u003e: Bottomland timber along drainage corridors connects roost sites to feeding areas and serves as travel routes. Turkeys move through these corridors consistently and predictably.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eBrushy Transitional Cover\\u003c/strong\\u003e: Areas of regenerating shrubs and young trees near established timber provide both food (insects, seeds, berries) and structural cover that turkeys use throughout the year.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eLicensing and What You Need\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eMichigan turkey licensing requires:\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cul\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eValid Michigan Hunting License\\u003c/strong\\u003e (base license)\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eMichigan Turkey License\\u003c/strong\\u003e — spring turkey licenses in most WMUs are allocated through the Limited License Application (LLA) draw. Check the MI DNR for over-the-counter availability in specific zones. Fall turkey may have different availability.\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eNon-residents must apply for non-resident turkey licenses; non-resident spring turkey licenses are highly sought and draw competition can be significant in popular WMUs\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003c/ul\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eThe key logistical point: you cannot purchase a spring turkey license over the counter at a sporting goods store the week of your hunt in most Michigan WMUs. You must apply through the draw system months in advance. Contact us early if you're planning a spring turkey hunt — we can advise on the application process and timeline, and we'll book you once you have your tag in hand.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eWhat We Supply vs. What You Bring\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eHotshot Outfitters provides:\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cul\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eGuide with 20+ years of Michigan turkey hunting experience\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003ePre-season turkey scouting on private properties\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eCalling expertise and decoy setup\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eGround blind (available — confirm at booking)\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eAccess to private woodlot and agricultural ground\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003c/ul\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eYou bring:\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cul\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eValid Michigan hunting license and turkey tag/license\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eShotgun (12-gauge or 20-gauge) or bow/crossbow if hunting archery\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eTurkey-specific shotgun loads: #4, #5, or #6 lead or comparable non-toxic loads; 3\\\" or 3.5\\\" shells for 12-gauge\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eFull camouflage — face, hands, everything\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eComfortable, quiet clothing and footwear — you may need to sit for extended periods and move quietly if repositioning\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eTurkey calls if you want to participate in calling (not required — your guide handles it)\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003c/ul\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eShotgun and Archery Turkey Hunting\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eMichigan's spring turkey season allows both shotgun and archery equipment during the designated season windows. Archery turkey hunting is a significant challenge — you need birds inside 40 yards (closer is better) and the draw sequence must happen without the bird seeing movement. Ground blinds are the standard solution for bowhunters, allowing you to draw without being detected.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eFor shotgun hunters, a full or extra-full turkey choke with premium turkey loads at 40 yards and under is the standard. Pattern your shotgun before your hunt and know your effective range. A well-placed shot at 25 yards is far better than a risky shot at 50.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eSome hunters use crossbows for turkey during archery season as well. Verify current Michigan regulations for crossbow use during specific turkey seasons at the MI DNR.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eSpring vs. Fall Turkey Hunting: Which Should You Book?\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eSpring\\u003c/strong\\u003e: The classic experience. Gobbling toms, warm mornings, hardwood timber waking up. Calling a gobbler into range when he's fired up on a May morning is some of the best hunting available anywhere in Michigan. Most hunters who hunt turkeys do it in spring.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eFall\\u003c/strong\\u003e: A fundamentally different challenge. Less vocal action, but the satisfaction of reading a flock, making the scatter, and calling birds back is its own reward. Fall hunting is less pressure-sensitive in many ways — birds haven't seen as many decoys and callers as spring birds have. A good fall morning in the oaks can be exceptional.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eWe guide both. Tell us which experience you're after and we'll book you into the right season.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eFrequently Asked Questions\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eQ: Do I need to apply for a Michigan turkey license in advance?\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eFor most Michigan WMUs, spring turkey licenses are allocated through the Limited License Application (LLA) draw process, with applications typically due in winter. You cannot walk in and buy a spring turkey license in April in limited-license zones. Plan ahead — contact us and we'll help you understand the timeline.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eQ: When do Michigan turkeys start gobbling in spring?\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eIn Huron County, gobblers typically begin consistent morning gobbling in mid-April as breeding activity increases. Peak gobbling typically coincides with hens going on their nests in early to mid-May, when toms become more responsive to calling because hens are not immediately available. Some of the best spring hunting in Michigan occurs in the first two weeks of May.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eQ: What time should I expect to be in the field for a spring turkey hunt?\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eYou should be set up and ready before first light — typically 30–45 minutes before sunrise. Gobblers fly down from roost at first light and that first hour is often the most productive of the morning. Your guide will advise on specific meet and setup times for your hunt.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eQ: Can I use an electronic call for turkey hunting in Michigan?\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eElectronic callers are prohibited for turkey hunting in Michigan during the spring and fall seasons. All calling must be done with hand calls or mouth calls. Your guide is an experienced caller and will handle calling — you're welcome to bring and use your own calls if you want to participate.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eQ: How far of a shot should I expect for turkey hunting?\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eMost shots on guided spring turkey hunts occur inside 40 yards, often inside 30. Pattern your shotgun at 20, 30, and 40 yards before your hunt to know your load's performance at each distance. Know your effective range and don't take marginal shots on birds at the edge of your pattern's effectiveness.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eQ: Can a first-time turkey hunter book a guided hunt?\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eAbsolutely. Spring turkey hunting is a great introduction to bird hunting — it's slower-paced than most waterfowl or upland hunting, the target is large, and the experience of calling a gobbler into range is immediately engaging for new hunters. Your guide will coach you through the experience.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eBook Your Michigan Turkey Hunt\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eWild turkey hunting in Michigan's Thumb — in the hardwood woodlots and agricultural edge cover of Huron County — is a genuine spring tradition. Hotshot Outfitters has guided turkey hunters on this ground for 20+ years, and when a fired-up gobbler comes drumming across a dew-covered field edge in April, you'll understand why we keep doing it.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eGet your turkey license drawn and give us a call to get on the schedule.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003ePhone:\\u003c/strong\\u003e (989) 551-4551 or (989) 670-4336\\n\\u003cstrong\\u003eAddress:\\u003c/strong\\u003e 6900 Huron City Road, Port Hope, MI 48468\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eApply for your license early. Spring season books up — don't wait.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,\"12:[[\\\"$\\\",\\\"script\\\",null,{\\\"type\\\":\\\"application/ld+json\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"{\\\\\\\"@context\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"https://schema.org\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"@type\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"Article\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"headline\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"Wild Turkey Hunting in Michigan | Guided Hunts with Hotshot Outfitters\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"description\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"Guided wild turkey hunting in Michigan's Thumb with Hotshot Outfitters. Spring and fall seasons in Huron County. 20+ years experience. Port Hope, MI.\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"image\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"https://hotshotoutfitters.com/images/michigan-hunting-wild-turkey-michigan-01.webp\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"author\\\\\\\":{\\\\\\\"@type\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"Organization\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"name\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"Hotshot Outfitters\\\\\\\"},\\\\\\\"publisher\\\\\\\":{\\\\\\\"@type\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"Organization\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"name\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"Hotshot Outfitters\\\\\\\"},\\\\\\\"mainEntityOfPage\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"https://hotshotoutfitters.com/hunts/wild-turkey\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"about\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"Wild Turkey hunting in Michigan\\\\\\\"}\\\"}}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"section\\\",null,{\\\"className\\\":\\\"relative pt-32 pb-16 lg:pt-40 lg:pb-24 overflow-hidden\\\",\\\"children\\\":[[\\\"$\\\",\\\"$L1b\\\",null,{\\\"src\\\":\\\"/images/michigan-hunting-wild-turkey-michigan-01.webp\\\",\\\"alt\\\":\\\"Michigan wild turkey gobbler taken on a guided spring hunt in Huron County\\\",\\\"fill\\\":true,\\\"priority\\\":true,\\\"sizes\\\":\\\"100vw\\\",\\\"className\\\":\\\"object-cover opacity-40\\\"}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"div\\\",null,{\\\"className\\\":\\\"absolute inset-0 bg-gradient-to-b from-pine-deep/70 via-pine-deep/70 to-pine-deep\\\"}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"div\\\",null,{\\\"className\\\":\\\"relative mx-auto max-w-5xl px-5 lg:px-8\\\",\\\"children\\\":[\\\"$\\\",\\\"$L1c\\\",null,{\\\"children\\\":[[\\\"$\\\",\\\"$L11\\\",null,{\\\"href\\\":\\\"/hunts\\\",\\\"className\\\":\\\"text-embe